e loft conversions of Printers' Row, and<br \/>\nCentral Station.","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_001604.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"74.5947265625","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Chicago Looks Ahead: 100 Years of Planning, 1909-2009,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, September 29\u2013December 1, 2010<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;http:\/\/digital-libraries.saic.edu\/u?\/mqc,8686&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"Chicago, cities, housing"},"resource_1605":{"resource_link":"..\/1605","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_001605.jpg","resource_title":"04. River City I, Clark Parkway Level, site plan (unbuilt), March 1974.","resource_description":"In 1968, architect Bertrand Goldberg began conceptualizing what was envisioned to become a<br \/>\ndynamic and affordable high density, mixed-use \"new city center\" along the southwestern outskirts<br \/>\nof Chicago's Loop. By 1970, construction of low and middle-income housing in Chicago, both<br \/>\nprivately and publicly funded, had nearly ceased, and the shortage was palpable. Known as River<br \/>\nCity, Goldberg's project was intended to help offset the decline in affordable rental units<br \/>\nadjacent to the central city. Unfortunately, Goldberg's early, sprawling plan of residential<br \/>\ntowers, mid-rise apartments, businesses, manufacturing, education, health care facilities,<br \/>\nreligious institutions, and parkland was never fully realized. Perceived conflict with the city's<br \/>\n\"Chicago 21\" plan and competing downtown developments such as Dearborn Park mired the project in<br \/>\npolitics for years. A greatly scaled-down River City&#151;one serpentine concrete mid-rise<br \/>\nresidential structure&#151;was eventually completed in 1984.","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_001605.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"33.08984375","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Chicago Looks Ahead: 100 Years of Planning, 1909-2009,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, September 29\u2013December 1, 2010<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;http:\/\/digital-libraries.saic.edu\/u?\/mqc,8703&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"Chicago, cities, housing, urban life"},"resource_1606":{"resource_link":"..\/1606","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_001606.jpg","resource_title":"05. Harry Weese notebook, sketches, and notes regarding plans for new CTA lines, 1975.","resource_description":"Architect Harry Weese, though perhaps best known for his design of Washington D.C.'s 100-mile<br \/>\nMetro subway system, with stations of coffered concrete vaults and undulating, embedded platform<br \/>\nlights, also studied Chicago's transit system extensively during the 1970s, perhaps in relation<br \/>\nto the 1968 Chicago Central Area Transit Project (CCATP). In this notebook, Weese sketches<br \/>\nhypothetical subway routes laid across a crudely-drawn map of the Loop. The CCATP was one of<br \/>\nseveral transit plans to suggest the replacement of the elevated Loop 'L' with a series of<br \/>\nsubways. Concerns over cost and feasibility delayed action on the plan until, in 1979, just as<br \/>\nconstruction was scheduled to begin on the Franklin Street Line [see dotted line on left side of<br \/>\npage], the project was terminated. From Weese's notebook: \"[C]onvenient drop off at the store...<br \/>\ntransit... like Orlando Disneyland or Expo 66... quiet new transit above glass and turn the street<br \/>\ninto a shopping mall (Woodfield).\"","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_001606.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"85.5087890625","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Chicago Looks Ahead: 100 Years of Planning, 1909-2009,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, September 29\u2013December 1, 2010<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;http:\/\/digital-libraries.saic.edu\/u?\/mqc,8503&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"Chicago, cities, city planning, trains, urban life"},"resource_1607":{"resource_link":"..\/1607","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_001607.jpg","resource_title":"06. <em>Chicago Metropolis 2020<\/em>, 2001.","resource_description":"Sponsored by the Commercial Club of Chicago&#151;the sponsor of Burnham's <em>Plan of Chicago<\/em> almost<br \/>\n100 years earlier&#151;Chicago Metropolis 2020 was unique and ambitious document in that it<br \/>\nsought \"to harmonize two seemingly warring impulses: privatism and public control.\" As Burnham's<br \/>\nplan once did, this plan put the business community in the driver's seat, with the expectation of<br \/>\nlocal and regional government collaboration. Though the plan's faith in the ability of the<br \/>\n\"wealth-creating market economy\" to provide for all appears unwavering, it nevertheless<br \/>\nacknowledged structural inequalities and failed public policy \"that encourages racial and ethnic<br \/>\nsegregation,\" noting that in the late 19th century, unlike now, \"Chicago's roaring industrial<br \/>\nplants were creating jobs [for unskilled workers] at an incredible rate. And the working poor had<br \/>\ninexpensive and efficient mass transit to get them to these jobs.\" These maps illustrate the<br \/>\nmovement of jobs to fewer and predominantly suburban locations between 1970 and 1990.","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_001607.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"44.00390625","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Chicago Looks Ahead: 100 Years of Planning, 1909-2009,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, September 29\u2013December 1, 2010","resource_tags_for_resource_id":""},"resource_1608":{"resource_link":"..\/1608","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_001608.jpg","resource_title":"07. <em>The Metropolis Housing Index: Housing as an Opportunity<\/em> brochure, 2003.","resource_description":"This report, prepared by Chicago Metropolis 2020, highlights the influential position which<br \/>\nhousing policy holds within the organization's regional plan. According to this document, \"[a]<br \/>\nhome is also a gateway to opportunity &#151; the most important connection to jobs, schools,<br \/>\ntransit, and community.\" The dearth of rental unit construction, significant increases in median<br \/>\nproperty and rental values, a trend towards geographically dispersed new job creation, increased<br \/>\ncommute times, and increased lack of affordable housing are all significant statistical<br \/>\nindicators described in this index, suggesting that only though changes in housing policy can the<br \/>\nChicago metropolitan area reach its full economic potential.","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_001608.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"37.5380859375","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Chicago Looks Ahead: 100 Years of Planning, 1909-2009,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, September 29\u2013December 1, 2010","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"Chicago, cities, city planning"}};
        
    (function($){
		$(document).ready(function(){
		    $("#reset").hide();
		    var galleryContent = $("#galleryContent"), gCEnd = galleryContent.children(".floatClear");
		    var types = new Array();
		    		    
		    $.each(galleryObjects, function(i, gObj) {
		        (function() {
		            types.push(gObj.resource_types_for_resource_id);
    				// build DOM objects and nest them through appends
    				var g = $('<div>', { 'class': 'galleryImage' } );
    				var gLink = $( '<a>', { 'href': gObj.resource_link } );
    				var gThumbnail = $( '<img src="' + gObj.resource_image_thumbnail + '" class="scaled" />' );
    				var gTooltip = $( "<div>", { "class": "tooltip", "html": '<img src="' + gObj.resource_image_thumbnail +'" alt="'+ gObj.resource_title +'" /><div id="artworkData"><strong>'+ gObj.resource_title +'</strong></div>' } );
    				gLink.append(gThumbnail);
    				gLink.append(gTooltip);
    				g.append(gLink);
			
    				// associate object to DOM object
    				g.artData = gObj;
				
    				// bind filtering events
    				g.bind( "filterByType", function(event,type) {
    					if ( $.inArray( type, $.map(g.artData.resource_types_for_resource_id.split(","), function(n){ return $.trim(n); }) ) == -1 ) { g.hide(); }
    					else { g.fadeIn(); }
    				});
    				
    				g.bind( "filterByTag", function(event,tag) {
    					if ( $.inArray( tag, $.map(g.artData.resource_tags_for_resource_id.split(","), function(n){ return $.trim(n); }) ) == -1 ) { g.hide(); }
    					else { g.fadeIn(); }
    				});
    				
    				g.bind( "filterReset", function(event){
    				    g.fadeIn();
    				});
			
    				// stolen from tooltip js
    				gTooltip.hide();		
    				// do rollovers for this link -- you can change the fadeIn and fadeOut to just show() and hide() if you don't like the fading effect
    				gLink.hover(
    				    function () {
        				    gTooltip.show();
        				    // position tooltip
            				gTooltip.css( { "bottom": gThumbnail.height()/2 + ( g.height() - gThumbnail.height() ) + "px", "left": gThumbnail.width()/2 + "px" } );
            			},
        			
        				function () { gTooltip.hide(); }
    				);
    				// end steal
			
    				// insert this gallery node before end of list
    				gCEnd.before(g);
			    })();
            });
            
            			
						
			//event resetting all filters
			$( "#reset a").click( function () {
			    $(".galleryImage").trigger( "filterReset" );
			    $("#count").text($('.galleryImage :visible').size());
			    $(".active").removeClass("active");
			    $("#reset").hide();
				return false;
			});
			
			$(".galleryImage img.scaled").each( function (index) {
                var img = $(this);
                var max = 112;
                // fix dimensions
                if ( img.height() > img.width() ){
                    img.css( { "height":max, "width":"auto"} );
                }
                else { img.css( { "height":"auto", "width":max} ); }
            });
		});
	})(jQuery);
</script> </div>
